00:00:01.180 --> 00:00:05.879
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: Hi everyone, I'm Winnie
Lam. Thank you so much for coming. It's my

00:00:05.879 --> 00:00:13.150
pleasure to welcome Dr. Iain Douglas-Hamilton
to Google for a talk today. So Iain has started

00:00:13.150 --> 00:00:19.289
saving the elephants probably before most
of us were born, looking at the room, certainly

00:00:19.289 --> 00:00:24.890
before I was born and before my parents were
married. He has been saving the elephants

00:00:24.890 --> 00:00:32.050
and working with local African people on conservation
efforts. He got his PhD in zoology from the

00:00:32.050 --> 00:00:38.040
University of Oxford in England and has received
many international awards recognizing him

00:00:38.040 --> 00:00:43.370
as a leading authority on African elephants.
Now, let me tell you a couple of interesting

00:00:43.370 --> 00:00:49.720
things about Iain. So, he's a pilot in addition
to being a conservationist, he flies his plane

00:00:49.720 --> 00:00:57.700
around a lot to track elephants. In addition
to flying his plane he's also crashed his

00:00:57.700 --> 00:01:01.000
plane a number of times.
[Laughter]

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:06.650
&gt;&gt;Presenter: And this is one of the times
when he's crashed his plane. Luckily, for

00:01:06.650 --> 00:01:10.720
the many times, actually not that many, for
the few times that he's crashed his plane,

00:01:10.720 --> 00:01:16.431
he's managed to walk away from it safe and
sound and he's with us, so lucky for us and

00:01:16.431 --> 00:01:21.610
lucky for him. Another interesting thing about
Iain is that he's Scottish and he likes to

00:01:21.610 --> 00:01:28.439
wear his kilt on special occasions. I'll show
you a picture here. He was receiving an award

00:01:28.439 --> 00:01:33.820
and he was wearing his Scottish kilt. And
depending on your opinion, it might be fortunate

00:01:33.820 --> 00:01:36.840
or unfortunate for us that he's not wearing
a kilt today.

00:01:36.840 --> 00:01:39.720
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Presenter: Anyways, without further ado,

00:01:39.720 --> 00:01:45.689
please help me give a very warm welcome to
Dr. Iain Douglas-Hamilton.

00:01:45.689 --> 00:01:48.530
[Applause]

00:01:48.530 --> 00:02:00.901
&gt;&gt;Iain: Okay, it's amazing to be here at Google.
When I first came across Google Earth, it

00:02:00.901 --> 00:02:07.290
just captured my imagination in a way that,
I didn't believe such a thing that I might

00:02:07.290 --> 00:02:14.010
have dreamed about, had actually been created.
And since then we've had a wonderful relationship

00:02:14.010 --> 00:02:22.349
with Google Earth outreach. I want to thank
very much, Charlie Knowles, who is my host

00:02:22.349 --> 00:02:30.969
on many occasions while I conservation network
which is an amazing outfit that helps introduce

00:02:30.969 --> 00:02:37.989
conservation entrepreneurs to very large donors.
Without taking anything on the way, they empower

00:02:37.989 --> 00:02:47.019
us to carry on our work in Africa. Also, I'd
like to acknowledge George Wittemyer, where

00:02:47.019 --> 00:02:56.079
are you George? Oh, there he is, George Wittemyer
and Jake Wall. George is our scientific chairman

00:02:56.079 --> 00:03:00.831
of our advisory board of “Save the Elephants"
and Jake is our Programmer and our Database

00:03:00.831 --> 00:03:07.849
Manager who looks after all our moving elephants
which, as you will hear, appear on Google

00:03:07.849 --> 00:03:18.499
Earth. My theme today is elephants in peril
because we're actually having an unprecedented

00:03:18.499 --> 00:03:26.269
surge at the moment in illegal killing of
elephants for ivory. We've come out of a twenty

00:03:26.269 --> 00:03:33.159
year lull period where we had a total ivory
trade ban. But now, once again, there's a

00:03:33.159 --> 00:03:42.989
rapidly increasing demand that is fueling
illegal killing and seizures of illegal ivory

00:03:42.989 --> 00:03:52.120
reached an all time high in 2011. So did another
measure of illegal killing which is part of

00:03:52.120 --> 00:03:58.680
the CITES Treaty which, in turn, is part of
UNEP that looks after endangered species.

00:03:58.680 --> 00:04:06.389
In some ways history's repeating itself and
I wanna take a minute just to go back to how

00:04:06.389 --> 00:04:16.109
I got started which was a long time ago in
1965. I went to live in a small park in Tanzania

00:04:16.109 --> 00:04:25.770
called Lake Manyara and I was very lucky to
work up a relationship with about 500 relatively

00:04:25.770 --> 00:04:31.870
habituated elephants and to learn to know
them as individuals. By the end of my time

00:04:31.870 --> 00:04:37.270
I was working with 50 families but it was
at that time I really learned to respect elephants.

00:04:37.270 --> 00:04:43.759
And, in fact, I don't think anyone knew before
that elephants, truly speaking, are a matriarchy

00:04:43.759 --> 00:04:50.680
and I learned the meaning of matriarchy; an
undaunted female intelligence who will go

00:04:50.680 --> 00:04:56.870
all the way out to save her family. That's
just what you're seeing here. This elephant

00:04:56.870 --> 00:05:02.759
is actually charging out in front of her family
while her family escapes, confronting the

00:05:02.759 --> 00:05:04.730
danger, which in this case was me.
[Laughter]

00:05:04.730 --> 00:05:07.659
&gt;&gt;Iain: I wasn't much of a danger but
[Laughter]

00:05:07.659 --> 00:05:14.750
&gt;&gt;Iain: she didn't know that. And, unfortunately,
because of this behavior, when female elephants

00:05:14.750 --> 00:05:20.759
come out to defend their families, they are
often the first victims. I want to show you

00:05:20.759 --> 00:05:25.500
a little piece of natural history before we
get onto other reasons for elephants being

00:05:25.500 --> 00:05:34.949
peril. This is a lone female who's defending
her baby against hyena attack, picture taken

00:05:34.949 --> 00:05:41.120
this year by someone called James Wells in
Botswana. And the hyenas are closing in on

00:05:41.120 --> 00:05:47.080
her baby from all directions and she's out
there defending, kicking with her feet, chasing

00:05:47.080 --> 00:05:56.320
them, scuffing up the dirt and at the end
of the day because of her very vigorous defense,

00:05:56.320 --> 00:06:03.969
the baby was safe although, unfortunately,
it lost its tail in the process. She's triumphant.

00:06:03.969 --> 00:06:09.680
Anyway, I lived, for these 5 first years of
my career, and I'm sorry I'm not telling you

00:06:09.680 --> 00:06:15.180
about it because that's the nice part of things
is living with elephants. And I brought up

00:06:15.180 --> 00:06:21.349
my family there, my two little girls, and
at the end of the 60's it was the end of an

00:06:21.349 --> 00:06:26.820
era, a golden era for the national parks,
a golden era for the elephants. And I became

00:06:26.820 --> 00:06:32.590
in a new problem, involved in a new problem,
this is how history is repeating itself, that

00:06:32.590 --> 00:06:41.870
the price of ivory suddenly, inexplicably
soared upwards in 1969, '70, '71. Now, in

00:06:41.870 --> 00:06:51.259
retrospect, we know that it was caused by
a surge in prosperity in Japan where ordinary

00:06:51.259 --> 00:06:59.169
people could all of a sudden afford to buy
ivory and it led to an ivory rush. So my next

00:06:59.169 --> 00:07:06.779
phase is I went out on a trip across Africa,
funded by the New York Zoological Society,

00:07:06.779 --> 00:07:10.690
to go and find out how many elephants there
were in Africa. And it took me to every corner

00:07:10.690 --> 00:07:16.590
of Africa, went in an airplane and to cut
a long story short, the ivory trade was out

00:07:16.590 --> 00:07:23.189
of control, the elephants were decreasing
fast and we came across scenes like this.

00:07:23.189 --> 00:07:31.939
Of whole families shot down with empty cartridge
cases and one worst case scenario, this particular

00:07:31.939 --> 00:07:40.139
herd were 150 survivors out of a population
that had been 8 thousand, five years earlier,

00:07:40.139 --> 00:07:45.879
just South of the Nile, so these things did
happen, they can happen. And it was in East

00:07:45.879 --> 00:07:52.990
Africa we saw the worst wipe-outs and recorded
them. Masses of ivory were leaving the continent.

00:07:52.990 --> 00:08:00.309
It took a very long time to get concerted
international action. So something like, something

00:08:00.309 --> 00:08:07.620
the order of 700 thousand elephants went out
in 10 years represented by about 700 tons

00:08:07.620 --> 00:08:17.689
of ivory a year. Then, in 1989, Kenya the
country which I live in now, took the lead

00:08:17.689 --> 00:08:23.340
and they took the ivory stockpile and they
sent the whole thing up in smoke as a statement

00:08:23.340 --> 00:08:30.309
to the world that they were no longer gonna
deal in ivory under the carpet. And this actually

00:08:30.309 --> 00:08:35.930
didn't, twenty years of cease fire, we were
great beneficiaries of this. I was able to

00:08:35.930 --> 00:08:42.490
go back to what I really love which is studying
elephant behavior, training up local people

00:08:42.490 --> 00:08:48.440
to do it and engaging scientists, young scientists
from abroad like George Wittemyer, to come

00:08:48.440 --> 00:08:56.889
out and make it a life's work as well. And
in Samburu, where we have our current research

00:08:56.889 --> 00:09:05.029
station, it's the most fabulous place you
can imagine. It's a place where, until recently,

00:09:05.029 --> 00:09:09.950
elephants could live out their lives without
being dominated by one emotion, which is fear

00:09:09.950 --> 00:09:19.740
of man. And so they behave naturally and it's
there that our prime technology was a very

00:09:19.740 --> 00:09:25.190
primitive one which was to learn to recognize
elephants as individuals, to record all the

00:09:25.190 --> 00:09:31.650
births and deaths and departures. We got to
know, again, about 500 elephants and we have

00:09:31.650 --> 00:09:40.199
been monitoring them for 15 years now, in
detail. However, the system did not work well

00:09:40.199 --> 00:09:46.540
to tell us how far the elephants went out
of the protected area and how they took their

00:09:46.540 --> 00:09:55.901
decisions to move. And for this we turned
to radio tracking using GPS technology. Each

00:09:55.901 --> 00:10:06.160
of these collars is a different type of ones
that we've been deploying and they gather

00:10:06.160 --> 00:10:11.430
the information on a chip and then send it
out either by satellite or GSM telephone.

00:10:11.430 --> 00:10:21.160
Here's an elephant coming to inspect the collars.
And the system, it now operates, we either

00:10:21.160 --> 00:10:26.630
download by a satellite or by a telephone
and it goes into a database which was designed

00:10:26.630 --> 00:10:32.699
by Jake Wall sitting in the back there. I'm
not going to go into all the details but the

00:10:32.699 --> 00:10:40.680
main feature is that it's recording the movements
of hundreds of elephants simultaneously, it

00:10:40.680 --> 00:10:50.730
goes into a database which for the moment
is on a server in a local cell telephone company,

00:10:50.730 --> 00:10:58.470
we're gonna move it onto the Cloud quite soon
and it can then relate, it can send out text

00:10:58.470 --> 00:11:08.550
messages to mobile telephones or to hand held
devices or to the internet. And what Jake

00:11:08.550 --> 00:11:15.430
has been developing for us is a series of
algorithms to detect changes in elephant behavior.

00:11:15.430 --> 00:11:21.050
This is very exciting and particularly in
relation to the current poaching surge that

00:11:21.050 --> 00:11:27.980
is going on. So I wanted to give you a little
example of an elephant in peril. This is an

00:11:27.980 --> 00:11:33.089
elephant called Mountain Bull and he lives
under this beautiful mount in Mount Kenya

00:11:33.089 --> 00:11:40.570
which is 17 thousand feet high, right on the
equator in the middle of Kenya. He has lots

00:11:40.570 --> 00:11:47.140
of difficult choices he has to make that involve
taking risks driven by the imperative to pass

00:11:47.140 --> 00:11:55.570
on his genes, he has to go and find females.
And sometimes because he needs to eat good

00:11:55.570 --> 00:12:02.100
food and grow strong so that he can compete
with other males for females, he has to take

00:12:02.100 --> 00:12:08.069
risks. And unfortunately this sometimes causes
a clash with people. So the little film excerpt

00:12:08.069 --> 00:12:18.990
I'm going to show, it's with my daughter who
once made films for the BBC and it is the

00:12:18.990 --> 00:12:24.620
story of following in the tracks of Mountain
Bull as he goes up this special corridor,

