00:17:09.530 --> 00:17:15.270
look from here or California or China or wherever
the hell you like and you can see what's happening

00:17:15.270 --> 00:17:23.150
to the elephants in real time. So it is amazing.
We open up our Google Earth and automatically

00:17:23.150 --> 00:17:29.131
these files spring out at us. We got, we're
tracking about 60 animals across Africa. This

00:17:29.131 --> 00:17:35.800
is all stuff that Jake has written and it's
a tiny little file that it's so easy to send

00:17:35.800 --> 00:17:43.350
to someone on email and it points into our
database and also Jake's managed to figure

00:17:43.350 --> 00:17:50.670
out how to make everybody's Google Earth automatically
update with the latest status. You not only

00:17:50.670 --> 00:17:58.520
get the latest position of each elephant coming
up but if we put a collar on a new elephant,

00:17:58.520 --> 00:18:06.350
it'll pop up in your Google Earth. The beauty
of the system is that without any GIS training,

00:18:06.350 --> 00:18:12.450
I can give it to anyone in Africa and we're
sharing it now far and wide, we're sharing

00:18:12.450 --> 00:18:17.790
our data with people who can actually help
to save the elephants. We're doing it in all

00:18:17.790 --> 00:18:27.890
sorts of different ways and we're using it
to detect if an animal starts moving too slowly.

00:18:27.890 --> 00:18:33.570
There's an algorithm that immediately says,
"This animal is going below its average speed."

00:18:33.570 --> 00:18:40.940
Now, it then pops up and we get an email report
every day with all the elephants on it and

00:18:40.940 --> 00:18:46.720
we have automatic alarms against each elephant
and we see whether the collar has failed to

00:18:46.720 --> 00:18:53.970
report and if so, for how many hours or days,
we see if the elephant is moving too slowly

00:18:53.970 --> 00:18:59.290
and several times when that has happened,
we've alerted a team that's gone out and sure

00:18:59.290 --> 00:19:04.440
enough, the elephant is wounded. And then
we get a veterinarian to come and dart the

00:19:04.440 --> 00:19:10.120
animal, put it down, give it drugs, clean
out the wound, put it back on its feet. But

00:19:10.120 --> 00:19:17.670
our most serious alarm of all is the immobility
alarm. So if the animal stops moving all together

00:19:17.670 --> 00:19:26.660
we get a warning and then we send out a patrol
and either the collar has fallen off the elephant

00:19:26.660 --> 00:19:32.050
or the elephant has been killed. At the moment
we're trying to hone this down. This is very

00:19:32.050 --> 00:19:39.930
much a system under development. We're experimenting
with accelerometers now and we've actually

00:19:39.930 --> 00:19:47.330
deployed our first accelerometers at Disney
in Florida. And a Disney scientist then came

00:19:47.330 --> 00:19:52.850
out to us and we've been working in the field.
We had an accelerometer on two elephants and

00:19:52.850 --> 00:19:58.020
we got a 48 hour cycle. So we were able to
look at what signal we're getting when the

00:19:58.020 --> 00:20:05.850
animal lies down and we want to actually get
it so sophisticated that we can tell the difference

00:20:05.850 --> 00:20:11.510
between lying down and being dead. Because
elephants do lie down, they lie down on their

00:20:11.510 --> 00:20:18.410
side, they go to sleep and they do it probably
twice a night, but if an elephant doesn't

00:20:18.410 --> 00:20:25.410
move for 3 hours that's very worrying. So
our automated alarm is graduated, if you get

00:20:25.410 --> 00:20:31.601
to a grade 3, that means no movements in 3
hours, that's bad. If it's a 4 or a 5, you

00:20:31.601 --> 00:20:38.670
get extremely worried and you send out a patrol.
So these are the various ways we can help

00:20:38.670 --> 00:20:46.190
them. And I just wanna show you the areas
